habitat_description:
Northwest/Southwest:
Primarily in oak woodlands; also found in riparian woodlands, rarely in conifer forests. In Monterey Co., CA, found among hills dominated by coast live (Quercus agrifolia) and valley (Q. lobata) oaks; in riparian areas, these oak species appear with willow (Salix spp.) and California sycamore (Platanus racemosa; Jenkins 1979). In Hastings Reservation, Monterey Co., found in 3 habitat types (Miller and Bock 1972): oak woodlands (mostly blue oak [Q. douglasii] and also valley oak) on north-facing slopes; exposed south-facing slopes with chaparral species (mostly chamise [Adenostoma fasciculatum]); and canyons and shaded areas with mixed woodland (live oak, California sycamore, big-leaf maple [Acer macrophyllum], and California laurel [Umbellularia californica], with brushy species such as willow and cream bush [Holodiscus discolor]). Found foraging in piñon pines (Pinus cembroides) in San Bernardino Mtns., CA (Short 1971). In Yuba Co., CA, found at 300 to 600 m elevation and associated most often with blue oak and interior live oak; also with California black oak (Q. kelloggii), gray pine (Pinus sabiniana), California buckeye (Aesculus californicus), and valley oak. In Madera Co., CA, found from 300 to 500 m, with blue oak and interior live oak, also gray pine and California buckeye. In Kern Co., CA, found from 1,100 to 1,700 m in blue oak woodlands, also valley oak, California black oak, interior live oak, and canyon live oak (Q. chrysolepis; Block 1991). In Marin Co., CA, sometimes found in open eucalyptus (Eucalyptus spp.) and cypress (Cupressus spp.) groves near riparian habitats (Shuford 1993). In nw. Baja California, found within desert at riparian sites permitting growth of cottonwoods (Populus spp.) and willows surrounded by chaparral; sites isolated in desert chaparral by “several miles” and “at least 2 miles [= 3.2 km]” (Short 1971)(quoted directly from Lowther 2000).
